In Solidity, it is not possible to directly modify a storage variable of a contract from an external library. External libraries can only access or modify their own internal storage.

If you need to modify a storage variable of a contract from an external library, you can define a public setter function in the contract and call that function from the library. Here's an example:

```solidity
pragma solidity ^0.8.0;

contract MyContract {
    uint256 public myVariable;

    function setMyVariable(uint256 newValue) public {
        myVariable = newValue;
    }
}

library MyLibrary {
    function updateVariable(MyContract contractInstance, uint256 newValue) external {
        contractInstance.setMyVariable(newValue);
    }
}
```

In this example, `MyContract` has a public storage variable `myVariable` and a `setMyVariable` function to modify it. `MyLibrary` has an `updateVariable` function that takes a `MyContract` instance and a new value. It then calls `setMyVariable` in the contract to update the storage variable.

By using the public setter function, you can change the storage variable of the contract from an external library.
